english:
  title: Reply to General Xiē of Xiangyang
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the fourth day of the seventh month in the second year of Zhonghe, your humble servant High [name] respectfully replies to General [name] at your residence.

    I have long gazed upon the records of antiquity and admired the sages of old. When one gifts others with words of utmost truth, such was Laozi's instruction; when a worthy friend brings one to completion, such was Guanzi's gratitude. Yet alas, the vulgar age grows ever more corrupt, and noble principles fade nearly to extinction. How could I have hoped that today I would witness their lingering influence? You alone, General, feared that jade might be obscured, and sought to polish away its flaws—thus you sent these luminous words afar. At first, reading your praise, sweat soaked through my robes; then upon your admonitions of support in peril, tears wetted my cheeks. Now that such radiance appears before me, how dare I respond carelessly? I place brush to paper to write forth my sincere heart—I only hope you will deign to examine it.

    Since last spring, I have known of bandits invading the frontier while the Emperor journeyed to Shu. Wishing to gather forces at Daliang, I dispatched proclamations to the outer garrisons, trained the soldiers, and set forth the day of departure. Suddenly Wuning rose in rebellion, first violating the borders of Sizhou, then crossing the Huai River. They spoke of guarding old domains like wolves, yet their true intent was to devour our territories like whales. With fierce formations they struck at our boundaries. Thus I sent forth detachments and succeeded in slaying the wicked. When summer came, I led out the greater army. Finding the northern routes blocked and arduous, I resolved instead to campaign westward for smooth passage.

    Then came imperial decree: "Your forces are few and your defensive concerns many. Guard only Huainan's borders, coordinate with Zhejiang's armies, and preserve Wu-Yue for me, sparing me eastern anxieties. Such service shall surely be immortal." Yet I reasoned that military momentum cannot halt of itself—the sovereign's command admits no refusal. Having already begun our campaign, we must advance. I read the winds and chose the day, eager only to soar forth. Then came another decree on the eleventh: "Armies from all regions attack on four fronts; victory is near. Do you block the bandits and supply provisions—why must you leave your post? This too is service to the throne. Should remnant traitors escape, swift deployment is essential."

    Receiving these second imperial words, I stationed my fleet, expanding means and supplying military needs. I advanced and retreated only by command, remained without fault from first to last—yet was suddenly slandered by nearby forces. The court grew suspicious. How dare I resent the fate of the swift horse consumed, or struggle against my racing hooves now bound? My loyalty unfolds not, and imperial favor seems distant. Yet I do not presume to betray the hearts of all—I merely preserve the strength of Huai's borderlands. In reason this has cause.

    You claim Sizhou anciently belonged to Pengmen, that I wrongly occupied and protected it, perhaps ignorant of cunning or deceived by rumor. But Xuzhou itself has long boasted false glory and refuses restraint. With growing power came increasing cruelty. From early fifth month I twice planned campaigns, deployed strong forces to aid the Prince, sent General Han Wen with a million strings of cash to relieve the commander-in-chief—all loaded aboard ships ready to depart—when suddenly Xuzhou raised arms to harass our borders, cut the Huai River, and built palisades, blocking our advance and unsettling our people.

    Examine closely Xuzhou's actions: they respond to Huang Chao's rebellion. How else explain how whenever we mobilize, his vicious bands assault us? How else their constant claim that Sizhou blocks the road to Bian? Linhuai stands isolated and weak—we barely hold it; Pengmen is strong and strategic—they grow reckless there. By this reckoning the pattern is clear. Moreover, the grain transports that once freely passed through Sizhou are now all detained by these bandits. Nearby Zhejiang and far Rong and Guang prefectures report nothing delivered—how then relieve the urgent crisis?

    Why I gathered Chu's forces to punish Xuzhou's wickedness is twofold: first, to obey imperial decree and rescue my neighboring domain; second, to stabilize the great Huai and march toward the capital's relief. It is not to covet Sizhou's taxes or challenge Xuzhou's strength—merely to distinguish right from wrong and preserve integrity throughout.

    For two years Sizhou has closed its gates; throughout the region smoke has ceased. Weavers set down their shuttles, farmers abandoned their plows. The garrison's provisions come from our own strained coffers; the prefecture's taxes cannot be wrung from exhausted people. Yet you claim I seize territorial advantage to make enemies of neighbors. Reading your letter, I find your deeper intent unclear.

    Sizhou did not merely boom during Xiantong's reign—it once kept the righteous way through the chaos of Tianbao. Moreover, when the Censor Yu Tao governed, his policies flourished and martial strategy perfected, earning the people's hearts and the army's devoted strength. Yet you would simply abandon it and ask no questions—how does reason support this?

    Xuzhou harbors great wickedness, no small threat. If you aid the cruel, how can you claim loyalty to the throne?

    What I now await is to slay the wolves of the way and soar like autumn eagles—to go swiftly with lightning strike. With Wang Linggong as my heart-brother, responding as head and tail unite, we shall master the snake formation, unfold the leopard's teachings, recover the capital, and welcome the imperial carriage. I shall not betray Moling's duty nor contest for prowess. My hope is to continue former labors and prevent future harms—that like Lian Xiangru my modest virtue not diminish our might, and like those who slandered Fei Wuji, all treacherous tongues meet their doom. Beyond this, nothing more need be said.

    I cherish your wise counsel as it dwells ever in my heart. I await your judgment with utmost respect. Your servant bows twice.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Wang Linggong (王令公): A military ally in the campaign against Huang Chao''s rebellion.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Lian Xiangru (藺相如): A historical exemplar of noble character who subordinated personal glory to state interests, referenced here as a model of undiminished worth through humility.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Fei Wuji (費無極): A historical figure infamous for his slanderous accusations, invoked here to represent treacherous court rivals.'
